1. Preparation and Overview¶

1.1 Business Understanding¶

FIFA is a famous football game, along with FM (football manager) and PES (Pro Evolution Soccer, renamed to eFootball now). Many football players themselves would play FIFA in their spare time, and care about their scores in the game. Due to its accurate scores, even clubs use it to look for high-potential young players.

To describe a football player, we can use a lot of evaluation indicators. Basically, every player (except goalkeepers) has a simple card with six general abilities:

  • Defending (DEF) - A players all-round defensive abilities, including tackling, heading and positioning.
  • Dribbling (DRI) - A players dribbling ability.
  • Pace (PAC) - The speed of a player.
  • Passing (PAS) - A players passing ability.
  • Physical (PHY) - A players overall physical attributes, including their strength.
  • Shooting (SHO)- The players shooting ability.

Every general ability has more detailed information called attributes. Different players have different attributes, which make them unique.

This dataset contains detailed attributes for every player registered in FIFA 19 (2019 edition). We want to use the attributes to predict the position for a player.

Predicting the position for an existing player makes no sense since we all know who he is, and which position he plays. However, there are two possible applications of our model.

First, many players may change position during their youth or early career, some players even change position in the late period of career. This model based on attributes can help coaches or players themselves to plan their career.

Second, PES has a game mode to create a player by user and add him to the game. We can also develop this here. A created player can have certain initial points and user can allocate these points to different attributes and the game might give a recommended position for the player. Also, the player can be totally randomly created by the game with a rational position.

Data attributes can be categorized into personal information, contract information, game information, position scores, and attributes describing football players' abilities that can be categorized into Physical, Mental, Skills.

  • Personal information: 'Unnamed: 0', 'ID', 'Name', 'Age', 'Photo', 'Nationality', 'Flag', 'Club', 'Club Logo', 'Value', 'Wage', 'Special', 'Preferred Foot', 'International Reputation', 'Weak Foot'
  • Contract information: 'Jersey Number', 'Joined', 'Loaned From', 'Contract Valid Until', 'Release Clause'
  • Game information: 'Overall', 'Potential', 'Skill Moves', 'Body Type', 'Real Face','Work Rate'
  • Position scores: 'LS', 'ST', 'RS', 'LW', 'LF', 'CF', 'RF', 'RW', 'LAM', 'CAM', 'RAM', 'LM', 'LCM', 'CM', 'RCM', 'RM', 'LWB', 'LDM', 'CDM', 'RDM', 'RWB', 'LB', 'LCB', 'CB', 'RCB', 'RB'

Attributes describing football players' abilities:

  • Physical: 'Acceleration','Stamina', 'Strength','SprintSpeed','Reactions','Jumping', 'Agility', 'Balance'
  • Mental: 'Aggression','Composure','Interceptions','Marking','Positioning','Vision'
  • Skills: 'Crossing', 'Finishing','HeadingAccuracy', 'ShortPassing', 'Volleys', 'Dribbling', 'Curve', 'FKAccuracy', 'LongPassing', 'BallControl', 'ShotPower', 'LongShots', 'Penalties', 'StandingTackle', 'SlidingTackle', 'GKDiving', 'GKHandling','GKKicking', 'GKPositioning', 'GKReflexes'

Personal information, contract information and game information are not related to the purpose of predicting players' postions, position scores was inclued in 'Position' attribute. So these attributes will be dropped off.

However, work rate of gameinfo will be kept as the category data in the data set. Among all the category attribute, we think work rate is mostly related to the purpose of predicting players' postions since players of different positions have different responsiblities for attack and defense.

The Work Rate is defined for Attacking (Attacking Work Rate - Abbreviated as AWR) and Defensive (Defensive Work Rate - Abbreviated as DWR) and rated between low, medium and high, which defines how a player puts effort to participates in attacks and defenses even when they are out of position.

Work rate attribute will be split into two attribute AWD and DWR, and the rate low, medium, high will be represented as 1,2,3.

1.2.3 Use proper variable representations.¶

In [6]:
def weight_to_int(df_weight):
    value = int(df_weight[:-3])  
    return value


def height_to_int(df_height):
    feet, dlm = map(int, df_height.split("'"))
    return round(feet * 12 + dlm * 2.54, 0)


data['Weight_int'] = data['Weight'].apply(weight_to_int)
data['Height_int'] = data['Height'].apply(height_to_int)
data = data.drop('Height', axis=1)
data = data.drop('Weight', axis=1)


# Attacking Work Rate - Abbreviated as AWR
def work_rate_AWR(df_work_rate):
    dic = {"High": 3, "Medium": 2, "Low": 1}
    AWR = dic[df_work_rate.split("/")[0]]
    return AWR


#  Defensive Work Rate - Abbreviated as DWR
def work_rate_DWR(df_work_rate):
    dic = {"High": 3, "Medium": 2, "Low": 1}
    DWR = dic[df_work_rate.split("/ ")[1]]
    return DWR


data['AWR'] = data["Work Rate"].apply(work_rate_AWR)
data['DWR'] = data["Work Rate"].apply(work_rate_DWR)
data = data.drop("Work Rate", axis=1)

2. Modeling (5 points total)¶

2.1 One-versus-all logistic regression classifier¶

In [13]:
class MultiClassLogisticRegression:
    def __init__(self, eta=1, iterations=20,  C=0.0001, solver="bfgs", regulation="L2",l1_ratio=0.1):
        if regulation not in "L1, L2, elasticnet, None":
            print("regulation not recognized. Defaulting to L2.")
            regulation="L2"
        if solver not in "stochastic-gradient-descent, steepest-descent, newton-cg, bfgs":
            print("solver not recognized. Defaulting to bfgs.")
            solver="bfgs"
        self.eta = eta
        self.iters = iterations
        self.C = C
        self.solver = solver
        self.regu = regulation
        self.l1_ratio=l1_ratio
        self.classifiers_ = []
        # internally we will store the weights as self.w_ to keep with sklearn conventions
        # convenience, private:
        
    @staticmethod
    def _add_bias(X):
        return np.hstack((np.ones((X.shape[0],1)),X)) # add bias term

    @staticmethod
    def _sigmoid(theta):
        # increase stability, redefine sigmoid operation
        return expit(theta) #1/(1+np.exp(-theta))
    
    @staticmethod
    def _L1(gradient,w,C):
        for i in range(1,w.shape[0]):
            if w[i] !=0:
                gradient[i] += -1 * C * (w[i])/np.abs(w[i])
            else:
                gradient[i] += 0
        return gradient
    
    @staticmethod
    def _L2(gradient,w,C):
        gradient[1:] += -2 * w[1:] * C
        return gradient
    
    @staticmethod
    def _elasticnet(gradient,w,C,l1_ratio):
        for i in range(1,w.shape[0]):
            if w[i] !=0:
                gradient[i] += -2 * w[i] * C * (1-l1_ratio) -1 * C * (w[i])/np.abs(w[i]) *l1_ratio
            else:
                gradient[i] += -2 * w[i] * C * (1-l1_ratio)
        return gradient

    
        
    @staticmethod
    def objective_function(w,X,y,C,l1_ratio,regulation):
        g = expit(X @ w)
        # invert this because scipy minimizes, but we derived all formulas for maximzing
        return -np.sum(ma.log(g[y==1]))-np.sum(ma.log(1-g[y==0])) + C*sum(w**2) 
        #-np.sum(y*np.log(g)+(1-y)*np.log(1-g))

    @staticmethod
    def objective_gradient(w,X,y,C,l1_ratio,regulation):
        g = expit(X @ w)
        ydiff = y-g # get y difference
        gradient = np.mean(X * ydiff[:,np.newaxis], axis=0)
        gradient = gradient.reshape(w.shape)
        if regulation == "L2":
            gradient[1:] += -2 * w[1:] * C
        elif regulation == "L1":
            gradient[1:] += -1 * C
        elif regulation == "elasticnet":
            gradient[1:] += -2 * w[1:] * C * (1-l1_ratio) -1 * C * l1_ratio
        elif regulation == None:
            gradient=gradient
        return -gradient
    
    @staticmethod
    def options():
        print("regulation: L1, L2, elasticnet, None")
        print("solver: stochastic-gradient-descent, steepest-descent, newton-cg, bfgs")
        print("C: regularization strength; must be a positive float. Larger values specify stronger regularization.")
        print("iterations: number of iterations taken for the solvers")
        print("eta: learning rate")
        print("l1_ratio:The Elastic-Net mixing parameter, with 0 <= l1_ratio <= 1. Only used if regulation='elasticnet'")
        return "----"
    
    def _get_gradient_newton(self,X,y):
        g = self._predict_proba(X,add_bias=False).ravel() # get sigmoid value for all classes
        ydiff = y-g # get y difference
        gradient = np.sum(X * ydiff[:,np.newaxis], axis=0) # make ydiff a column vector and multiply through
        gradient = gradient.reshape(self.w_.shape)
        if self.regu == "L2":
            hessian = X.T @ np.diag(g*(1-g)) @ X - 2 * self.C # calculate the hessian
            gradient=self._L2(gradient,self.w_,self.C)
        elif self.regu == "L1":
            hessian = X.T @ np.diag(g*(1-g)) @ X  # calculate the hessian
            gradient=self._L1(gradient,self.w_,self.C)
        elif self.regu == "elasticnet":
            hessian = X.T @ np.diag(g*(1-g)) @ X - 2 * self.C * self.l1_ratio # calculate the hessian
            gradient=self._elasticnet(gradient,self.w_,self.C,self.l1_ratio)
        elif self.regu == None:
            gradient=gradient
        return pinv(hessian) @ gradient
               
    def _get_gradient_steepest(self,X,y):
        ydiff = y-self._predict_proba(X,add_bias=False).ravel() # get y difference
        gradient = np.mean(X * ydiff[:,np.newaxis], axis=0) # make ydiff a column vector and multiply through
        gradient = gradient.reshape(self.w_.shape)
        if self.regu == "L2":
            gradient=self._L2(gradient,self.w_,self.C)
        elif self.regu == "L1":
            gradient=self._L1(gradient,self.w_,self.C)
        elif self.regu == "elasticnet":
            gradient=self._elasticnet(gradient,self.w_,self.C,self.l1_ratio)
        elif self.regu == None:
            gradient=gradient
        return gradient

    def _get_gradient_stochastic(self,X,y):
        idx = int(np.random.rand()*len(y)) # grab random instance
        ydiff = y[idx]-self._predict_proba(X[idx],add_bias=False) # get y difference (now scalar)
        gradient = X[idx] * ydiff[:,np.newaxis] # make ydiff a column vector and multiply through
        gradient = gradient.reshape(self.w_.shape)
        if self.regu == "L2":
            gradient=self._L2(gradient,self.w_,self.C)
        elif self.regu == "L1":
            gradient=self._L1(gradient,self.w_,self.C)
        elif self.regu == "elasticnet":
            gradient=self._elasticnet(gradient,self.w_,self.C,self.l1_ratio)
        elif self.regu == None:
            gradient=gradient
        return gradient
      
    # choose the optimization method     
    def _get_gradient(self,X,y):
        if self.solver=="stochastic-gradient-descent":
            return self._get_gradient_stochastic(X,y)
        elif self.solver=="steepest-descent":
            return self._get_gradient_steepest(X,y)
        elif self.solver == "newton-cg":
            return self._get_gradient_newton(X,y)
            
    # public for binary classification:
    def _predict_proba(self,X,add_bias=True):
        # add bias term if requested
        Xb = self._add_bias(X) if add_bias else X
        return self._sigmoid(Xb @ self.w_) # return the probability y=1

    def _predict(self,X):
        return (self._predict_proba(X)>0.5) #return the actual prediction


    def _fit(self, X, y):
        Xb = self._add_bias(X) # add bias term
        num_samples, num_features = Xb.shape

        self.w_ = np.zeros((num_features,1)) # init weight vector to zeros

        # for as many as the max iterations
        for _ in range(self.iters):
            gradient = self._get_gradient(Xb,y)
            self.w_ += gradient*self.eta # multiply by learning rate 
            # add bacause maximizing 
            
    # fit function using bfgs for binary classification:
    def _fit_bfgs(self, X, y):
        Xb = self._add_bias(X) # add bias term
        num_samples, num_features = Xb.shape

        self.w_ = fmin_bfgs(self.objective_function, # what to optimize
                            np.zeros((num_features,1)), # starting point
                            fprime=self.objective_gradient, # gradient function
                            args=(Xb,y,self.C,self.l1_ratio,self.regu), # extra args for gradient and objective function
                            gtol=1e-03, # stopping criteria for gradient, |v_k|
                            maxiter=self.iters, # stopping criteria iterations
                            disp=False)
        self.w_ = self.w_.reshape((num_features,1))
        
    # public  for one-versus-all classification:   
    def fit(self,X,y):
        num_samples, num_features = X.shape
        self.unique_ = np.sort(np.unique(y)) # get each unique class value
        num_unique_classes = len(self.unique_)
        self.classifiers_ = []
        for i,yval in enumerate(self.unique_): # for each unique value
            y_binary = np.array(y==yval).astype(int) # create a binary problem
            # train the binary classifier for this class
            hblr = MultiClassLogisticRegression(eta=self.eta,iterations=self.iters,C=self.C,l1_ratio=self.l1_ratio,regulation=self.regu,solver=self.solver)
            # choose fit function 
            fit_function=hblr._fit_bfgs if hblr.solver =="bfgs" else hblr._fit
            fit_function(X,y_binary)
            # add the trained classifier to the list
            self.classifiers_.append(hblr)
        # save all the weights into one matrix, separate column for each class
        self.w_ = np.hstack([x.w_ for x in self.classifiers_]).T
        
    def predict_proba(self,X):
        probs = []
        for hblr in self.classifiers_:
            probs.append(hblr._predict_proba(X).reshape((len(X),1))) # get probability for each classifier
        
        return np.hstack(probs) # make into single matrix
    
    def predict(self,X):
        return np.argmax(self.predict_proba(X),axis=1) # take argmax along row

From the parameter grid search plot, we can see, the best parameter is C = 0.0215 when using newton-cg optimization

We think there are some "data snooping" involved with this method of selecting parameters.

Frist, we should split data into train set, validation set and test set, and do the parameter search using validation set. Because when do the parameter search on test set, the model also learns from the test set data. In this case, when we predict a new data set which has not been learn by the model, the accuracy may not be as high as that of test set.

Second, scaling the data set before spliting into train-test set will also include data snooping problem, because the scaled data shares the same mean, maximum and minimum values. The training data should be scaled independently of the test data"

3. Deployment¶

We want to deploy this model to the game or a web server. As this game updates annually, it doesn't require frequent trainings, so we can just provide our pre-trained model. In this circumstance, accuracy is more important than the training time.

Although our model needs more training time but has better accuracy than sci-kit learn, we will still use ours.

4. Exceptional Work¶

For logistic regression, we can calculate the formula for the $j^{th}$ and $k^{th}$ element of the Hessian as follows:

$$ \mathbf{H}_{j,k}(\mathbf{w}) = \frac{\partial}{\partial w_k} \underbrace{\frac{\partial}{\partial w_j}J(\mathbf{w})}_{\text{first derivative}} $$$$ J(\mathbf{w}) = \sum_i (y^{(i)}-g(\mathbf{w}^T\cdot\mathbf{x}^{(i)}))^{2} $$

the result of the $j^{th}$ partial derivative $\nabla J(\mathbf{w})$:

$$ \frac{\partial}{\partial w_j}J(\mathbf{w}) = \sum_i \left (-2 *[y^{(i)}*g(\mathbf{w}^T\cdot\mathbf{x}^{(i)})-g(\mathbf{w}^T\cdot\mathbf{x}^{(i)})^{2}-y^{(i)}*g(\mathbf{w}^T\cdot\mathbf{x}^{(i)})^{2}+g(\mathbf{w}^T\cdot\mathbf{x}^{(i)})^{3}]\right)x_j^{(i)} $$

So we can plug this back into the equation to get:

$$ \begin{split} \mathbf{H}_{j,k}(\mathbf{w}) & = \frac{\partial}{\partial w_k} \sum_i \left(-2 *[y^{(i)}*g(\mathbf{w}^T\cdot\mathbf{x}^{(i)})-g(\mathbf{w}^T\cdot\mathbf{x}^{(i)})^{2}-y^{(i)}*g(\mathbf{w}^T\cdot\mathbf{x}^{(i)})^{2}+g(\mathbf{w}^T\cdot\mathbf{x}^{(i)})^{3}]\right)x_j^{(i)}\\ & = \sum_{i=1}^M \left[-2 *[y^{(i)}-2*g(\mathbf{w}^T\cdot\mathbf{x}^{(i)})-2*y^{(i)}*g(\mathbf{w}^T\cdot\mathbf{x}^{(i)})+3*g(\mathbf{w}^T\cdot\mathbf{x}^{(i)})^{2}]*g(\mathbf{w}^T\cdot\mathbf{x}^{(i)})(1-g(\mathbf{w}^T\cdot\mathbf{x}^{(i)}))\right]\cdot{x_k}^{(i)}{x_j}^{(i)} \\ \end{split} $$

So the get_gradient function can be update as follows:

def _get_gradient_newton_mse(self,X,y): g = self._predict_proba(X,add_bias=False).ravel() # get sigmoid value for all classes ydiff = y-g # get y difference gradient = np.sum(X * ydiff[:,np.newaxis], axis=0) # make ydiff a column vector and multiply through gradient = gradient.reshape(self.w_.shape) if self.regu == "L2": hessian = X.T @ np.diag(2*(3*g*g-2*g*y-2*g+y)*g*(1-g)) @ X - 2 * self.C # calculate the hessian gradient=self._L2(gradient,self.w_,self.C) elif self.regu == "L1": hessian = X.T @ np.diag(2*(3*g*g-2*g*y-2*g+y)*g*(1-g)) @ X # calculate the hessian gradient=self._L1(gradient,self.w_,self.C) elif self.regu == "elasticnet": hessian = X.T @ np.diag(2*(3*g*g-2*g*y-2*g+y)*g*(1-g)) @ X - 2 * self.C * self.l1_ratio # calculate the hessian gradient=self._elasticnet(gradient,self.w_,self.C,self.l1_ratio) elif self.regu == None: gradient=gradient return pinv(hessian) @ gradient

class MultiClassLogisticRegression:
    def __init__(self, eta, iterations=20,  C=0.0001, solver="newton-cg", regulation="L2",l1_ratio=0.1):
        if regulation not in "L1,L2, elasticnet, None":
            print("regulation not recognized. Defaulting to L2.")
            regulation="L2"
        self.eta = eta
        self.iters = iterations
        self.C = C
        self.solver = solver
        self.regu = regulation
        self.l1_ratio=l1_ratio
        self.classifiers_ = []
        # internally we will store the weights as self.w_ to keep with sklearn conventions
        # convenience, private:
        
    @staticmethod
    def _add_bias(X):
        return np.hstack((np.ones((X.shape[0],1)),X)) # add bias term

    @staticmethod
    def _sigmoid(theta):
        # increase stability, redefine sigmoid operation
        return expit(theta) #1/(1+np.exp(-theta))
    
    @staticmethod
    def _L1(gradient,w,C):
        for i in range(1,w.shape[0]):
            if w[i] !=0:
                gradient[i] += -1 * C * (w[i])/np.abs(w[i])
            else:
                gradient[i] += 0
        return gradient
    
    @staticmethod
    def _L2(gradient,w,C):
        gradient[1:] += -2 * w[1:] * C
        return gradient
    
    @staticmethod
    def _elasticnet(gradient,w,C,l1_ratio):
        for i in range(1,w.shape[0]):
            if w[i] !=0:
                gradient[i] += -2 * w[i] * C * (1-l1_ratio) -1 * C * (w[i])/np.abs(w[i])
            else:
                gradient[i] += -2 * w[i] * C * (1-l1_ratio)
        return gradient

    
        
    @staticmethod
    def objective_function(w,X,y,C,l1_ratio,regulation):
        g = expit(X @ w)
        # invert this because scipy minimizes, but we derived all formulas for maximzing
        return -np.sum(ma.log(g[y==1]))-np.sum(ma.log(1-g[y==0])) + C*sum(w**2) 
        #-np.sum(y*np.log(g)+(1-y)*np.log(1-g))

    @staticmethod
    def objective_gradient(w,X,y,C,l1_ratio,regulation):
        g = expit(X @ w)
        ydiff = y-g # get y difference
        gradient = np.mean(X * ydiff[:,np.newaxis], axis=0)
        gradient = gradient.reshape(w.shape)
        if regulation == "L2":
            gradient[1:] += -2 * w[1:] * C
        elif regulation == "L1":
            gradient[1:] += -1 * C
        elif regulation == "elasticnet":
            gradient[1:] += -2 * w[1:] * C * (1-l1_ratio) -1 * C * l1_ratio
        elif regulation == None:
            gradient=gradient
        return -gradient
    
    @staticmethod
    def options():
        print("regulation: L1, L2, elasticnet, None")
        print("solver: stochastic-gradient-descent, steepest-descent, newton-cg, bfgs")
    
    def _get_gradient_newton(self,X,y):
        g = self._predict_proba(X,add_bias=False).ravel() # get sigmoid value for all classes
        ydiff = y-g # get y difference
        gradient = np.sum(X * ydiff[:,np.newaxis], axis=0) # make ydiff a column vector and multiply through
        gradient = gradient.reshape(self.w_.shape)
        if self.regu == "L2":
            hessian = X.T @ np.diag(g*(1-g)) @ X - 2 * self.C # calculate the hessian
            gradient=self._L2(gradient,self.w_,self.C)
        elif self.regu == "L1":
            hessian = X.T @ np.diag(g*(1-g)) @ X  # calculate the hessian
            gradient=self._L1(gradient,self.w_,self.C)
        elif self.regu == "elasticnet":
            hessian = X.T @ np.diag(g*(1-g)) @ X - 2 * self.C * self.l1_ratio # calculate the hessian
            gradient=self._elasticnet(gradient,self.w_,self.C,self.l1_ratio)
        elif self.regu == None:
            gradient=gradient
        return pinv(hessian) @ gradient
    def _get_gradient_newton_mse(self,X,y):
        g = self._predict_proba(X,add_bias=False).ravel() # get sigmoid value for all classes
        ydiff = y-g # get y difference
        gradient = np.sum(X * ydiff[:,np.newaxis], axis=0) # make ydiff a column vector and multiply through
        gradient = gradient.reshape(self.w_.shape)
        if self.regu == "L2":
            hessian = X.T @ np.diag(2*(3*g*g-2*g*y-2*g+y)*g*(1-g)) @ X - 2 * self.C # calculate the hessian
            gradient=self._L2(gradient,self.w_,self.C)
        elif self.regu == "L1":
            hessian = X.T @ np.diag(2*(3*g*g-2*g*y-2*g+y)*g*(1-g)) @ X  # calculate the hessian
            gradient=self._L1(gradient,self.w_,self.C)
        elif self.regu == "elasticnet":
            hessian = X.T @ np.diag(2*(3*g*g-2*g*y-2*g+y)*g*(1-g)) @ X  - 2 * self.C * self.l1_ratio # calculate the hessian
            gradient=self._elasticnet(gradient,self.w_,self.C,self.l1_ratio)
        elif self.regu == None:
            gradient=gradient
        return pinv(hessian) @ gradient
    def _get_gradient_steepest(self,X,y):
        ydiff = y-self._predict_proba(X,add_bias=False).ravel() # get y difference
        gradient = np.mean(X * ydiff[:,np.newaxis], axis=0) # make ydiff a column vector and multiply through
        gradient = gradient.reshape(self.w_.shape)
        if self.regu == "L2":
            gradient=self._L2(gradient,self.w_,self.C)
        elif self.regu == "L1":
            gradient=self._L1(gradient,self.w_,self.C)
        elif self.regu == "elasticnet":
            gradient=self._elasticnet(gradient,self.w_,self.C,self.l1_ratio)
        elif self.regu == None:
            gradient=gradient
        return gradient

    def _get_gradient_stochastic(self,X,y):
        idx = int(np.random.rand()*len(y)) # grab random instance
        ydiff = y[idx]-self._predict_proba(X[idx],add_bias=False) # get y difference (now scalar)
        gradient = X[idx] * ydiff[:,np.newaxis] # make ydiff a column vector and multiply through
        gradient = gradient.reshape(self.w_.shape)
        if self.regu == "L2":
            gradient=self._L2(gradient,self.w_,self.C)
        elif self.regu == "L1":
            gradient=self._L1(gradient,self.w_,self.C)
        elif self.regu == "elasticnet":
            gradient=self._elasticnet(gradient,self.w_,self.C,self.l1_ratio)
        elif self.regu == None:
            gradient=gradient
        return gradient
        
    def _get_gradient(self,X,y):
        if self.solver=="stochastic-gradient-descent":
            return self._get_gradient_stochastic(X,y)
        elif self.solver=="steepest-descent":
            return self._get_gradient_steepest(X,y)
        elif self.solver == "newton-cg":
            return self._get_gradient_newton(X,y)
        elif self.solver == "newton-cg-mse":
            return self._get_gradient_newton_mse(X,y)
        
        
    
    def _fit_bfgs(self, X, y):
        Xb = self._add_bias(X) # add bias term
        num_samples, num_features = Xb.shape

        self.w_ = fmin_bfgs(self.objective_function, # what to optimize
                            np.zeros((num_features,1)), # starting point
                            fprime=self.objective_gradient, # gradient function
                            args=(Xb,y,self.C,self.l1_ratio,self.regu), # extra args for gradient and objective function
                            gtol=1e-03, # stopping criteria for gradient, |v_k|
                            maxiter=self.iters, # stopping criteria iterations
                            disp=False)
        self.w_ = self.w_.reshape((num_features,1))
        
            
    # public:
    def _predict_proba(self,X,add_bias=True):
        # add bias term if requested
        Xb = self._add_bias(X) if add_bias else X
        return self._sigmoid(Xb @ self.w_) # return the probability y=1

    def _predict(self,X):
        return (self._predict_proba(X)>0.5) #return the actual prediction


    def _fit(self, X, y):
        Xb = self._add_bias(X) # add bias term
        num_samples, num_features = Xb.shape

        self.w_ = np.zeros((num_features,1)) # init weight vector to zeros

        # for as many as the max iterations
        for _ in range(self.iters):
            gradient = self._get_gradient(Xb,y)
            self.w_ += gradient*self.eta # multiply by learning rate 
            # add bacause maximizing 
            
    def fit(self,X,y):
        num_samples, num_features = X.shape
        self.unique_ = np.sort(np.unique(y)) # get each unique class value
        num_unique_classes = len(self.unique_)
        self.classifiers_ = []
        for i,yval in enumerate(self.unique_): # for each unique value
            y_binary = np.array(y==yval).astype(int) # create a binary problem
            # train the binary classifier for this class
            hblr = MultiClassLogisticRegression(eta=self.eta,iterations=self.iters,C=self.C,l1_ratio=self.l1_ratio,regulation=self.regu,solver=self.solver)
            fit_function=hblr._fit_bfgs if hblr.solver =="bfgs" else hblr._fit
            fit_function(X,y_binary)
            # add the trained classifier to the list
            self.classifiers_.append(hblr)
        # save all the weights into one matrix, separate column for each class
        self.w_ = np.hstack([x.w_ for x in self.classifiers_]).T
    def predict_proba(self,X):
        probs = []
        for hblr in self.classifiers_:
            probs.append(hblr._predict_proba(X).reshape((len(X),1))) # get probability for each classifier
        
        return np.hstack(probs) # make into single matrix
    
    def predict(self,X):
        return np.argmax(self.predict_proba(X),axis=1) # take argmax along row

In [25]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots()

ax.plot(range(1,11), mse_accs, label='mean-squared error')
ax.plot(range(1,11), log_accs, label='maximum likelihood')

ax.set_ylabel('Accuracy')
ax.set_xlabel('Iterations')
ax.legend()

plt.show()

maximum likelihood is prefered.

Because maximum likelihood loss function is convex, it is guranteed to find a global minimum as we can see from the above plot, with iteration increasing, the accuracy is increasing.

However, mean-squared error loss function is not convex, it is not guranteed find a global minimum. And in high dimensions, Newton's method can converge to a saddle point instead of to a local minimum, which explains even at second step it finds the minimum(the highest accuracy), however with iteration increasing, it converge to a saddle point.
